Murders and shootings are up in New York City, and it's not just a 'spike', analyst says: 'We're in uncharted waters." Insider Oct 27, 2020


When New York City shut down in March, crime stat analysts watched in awe as homicide and shooting counts kept falling. When summer rolled around, though, the violence returned in earnest. And in addition to the expected uptick that comes each year during warmer weather, the city made up for the crime that didn't occur in March, April, and May. Then it went even further. As of September, there was a 33.2% increase in the number of murders compared to the same time last year, according to city crime statistics. The number of shooting victims has also jumped 102%.
